<subSubSection pageId="35" pageNumber="36" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="35.[136,1452,158,437]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">
<emphasis box="[136,245,158,184]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">Perennial</emphasis>
, rosetted, acaulescent or forming short columns densely covered by marcescent leaves. 
<emphasis box="[1236,1314,159,184]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">Leaves</emphasis>
decumbent, with geniculate-involute vernation, distinctly petiolate, spatulate, petiole abruptly broadening into lamina, petiole about as long as to slightly longer than the lamina, lamina obovate to suborbicular; stipule rectangular in outline, divided into laciniate segments from the base. 
<emphasis box="[674,741,267,293]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">Scape</emphasis>
erect at the base, glabrous, (30 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1103,1117,266,292]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">–</emphasis>
) 
<quantity box="[1125,1264,266,293]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.1" metricValueMax="1.5" metricValueMin="0.7" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" unit="mm" value="110.0" valueMax="150.0" valueMin="70.0">
70 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1155,1169,266,292]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">–</emphasis>
150 mm
</quantity>
long, (2 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1363,1377,266,292]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">–</emphasis>
)4 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1400,1414,266,292]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">–</emphasis>
12- flowered; pedicels about the same length as sepals or longer (always longer than half of the sepals’ length), 2 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1377,1391,302,328]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">–</emphasis>
4(
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1414,1428,302,328]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">–</emphasis>
6) mm long; sepals 
<quantity box="[333,470,338,365]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.5" metricValueMax="4.5" metricValueMin="2.5" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" unit="mm" value="3.5" valueMax="4.5" valueMin="2.5">
2.5 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[368,382,338,364]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">–</emphasis>
4.5 mm
</quantity>
long, ovate, united up to half length, apex acute to cuspidate, glabrous or sparsely to densely glandular-pilose, mostly at the base, erect in fruit; petals white; gynoecium 3-carpelate, styles bifurcated at the base. 
<emphasis box="[200,264,410,436]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">Seeds</emphasis>
ovoid, testa foveolate.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="35.[136,1452,482,1517]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[136,292,482,508]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">Illustrations:</emphasis>
Duno de Stefano (1995: 84, figs. 2a–f); 
<bibRefCitation author="Duno de Stefano, R. &amp; Culham, A." box="[761,1215,482,509]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" pagination="697 - 703" refId="ref54421" refString="Duno de Stefano, R. &amp; Culham, A. (1998) Droseraceae. In: Steyermark, J. A., Berry, P. E. &amp; Holst, B. K. (eds.) Flora of the Venezuelan Guayana 4. Missouri Botanical Garden Press, St Louis, pp. 697 - 703." type="book chapter" year="1998">Duno de Stefano &amp; Culham (1998: 701</bibRefCitation>
, fig. 555—habit and leaf).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="35" pageNumber="36" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="35.[136,1452,482,1517]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,345,554,580]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">Distribution:</emphasis>
— 
<collectingCountry box="[374,486,554,580]" name="Colombia" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">Colombia</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[498,616,554,580]" name="Venezuela" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">Venezuela</collectingCountry>
, and 
<collectingCountry box="[677,745,554,580]" name="Brazil" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">Brazil</collectingCountry>
(North: AM, RR; Fig. 8b). The species was only known from the north of the Rio Amazonas, but it is here first reported from the southern side, in the municipality of Novo Aripuanã (AM), however lacking georeferenced data [
<emphasis box="[635,820,626,652]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">Ramos et al. s.n.</emphasis>
(INPA-62135)].
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="35" pageNumber="36" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="35.[136,1452,482,1517]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,291,662,688]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">Habitat:</emphasis>
—Lowland wet savannas and highland rock outcrops in sandy soils or cracks of sandstone in wet areas, between 
<quantity box="[236,363,698,725]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.9" metricValueMax="17.0" metricValueMin="0.8" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" unit="m" value="890.0" valueMax="1700.0" valueMin="80.0">
80 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[264,278,698,724]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">–</emphasis>
1700 m
</quantity>
a.s.l.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="35.[136,1452,482,1517]" box="[189,1004,734,761]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,351,734,760]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">Phenology:—</emphasis>
Collected in flower in January, February, July and August.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="35" pageNumber="36" type="conservation">
<paragraph blockId="35.[136,1452,482,1517]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,442,770,796]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">Conservation status:</emphasis>
—Least Concern (LC). 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Maguire &amp; Wurdack" authorityYear="1957" baseAuthorityName="Steyermark" baseAuthorityYear="1952" box="[724,958,770,796]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Droseraceae" genus="Drosera" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="esmeraldae">
<emphasis box="[724,958,770,796]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">Drosera esmeraldae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is widespread in a relatively remote and preserved area (
<collectingCountry box="[318,392,806,832]" name="Brazil" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">Brazil</collectingCountry>
: AOO= 
<quantity box="[480,552,806,832]" metricMagnitude="4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.2" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" unit="km" value="32.0">32 km</quantity>
<superScript attach="left" box="[552,560,806,820]" fontSize="6" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">2</superScript>
, EOO= 
<quantity box="[649,758,806,832]" metricMagnitude="6" metricUnit="m" metricValue="9.898" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" unit="km" value="9898.0">9,898 km</quantity>
<superScript attach="left" box="[757,765,806,820]" fontSize="6" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">2</superScript>
; global: AOO= 
<quantity box="[946,1031,806,832]" metricMagnitude="5" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.04" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" unit="km" value="104.0">104 km</quantity>
<superScript attach="left" box="[1031,1039,806,820]" fontSize="6" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">2</superScript>
, EOO= 
<quantity box="[1128,1265,806,833]" metricMagnitude="8" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.61316" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" unit="km" value="561316.0">561,316 km</quantity>
<superScript attach="left" box="[1265,1273,806,820]" fontSize="6" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">2</superScript>
). In 
<collectingCountry box="[1331,1399,806,832]" name="Brazil" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">Brazil</collectingCountry>
it is found inside the Serra do Aracá State Park (AM).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="35" pageNumber="36" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="35.[136,1452,482,1517]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,265,878,904]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">Notes:</emphasis>
— 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Maguire &amp; Wurdack" authorityYear="1957" baseAuthorityName="Steyermark" baseAuthorityYear="1952" box="[294,523,878,904]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Droseraceae" genus="Drosera" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="esmeraldae">
<emphasis box="[294,523,878,904]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">Drosera esmeraldae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is more similar to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Poiret" authorityYear="1804" box="[739,882,878,904]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Droseraceae" genus="Drosera" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="capillaris">
<emphasis box="[739,882,878,904]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">D. capillaris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, from which it is distinguished by longer pedicels relative to sepal length, sepals with acute to cuspidate apex, and seeds with foveolate testa (
<emphasis box="[1179,1202,915,940]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">vs</emphasis>
. pedicels shorter than the sepals, sepals with obtuse apex and seed with papillose testa; 
<tableCitation box="[864,948,950,976]" captionStart="TABLE 3" captionStartId="21.[136,229,1487,1513]" captionTargetId="graphics-577@21.[136,1449,1593,1971]" captionTargetPageId="21" captionText="TABLE 3. Diagnostic characters distinguishing between Drosera amazonica, D. biflora, D. capillaris (only specimens" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">Table 3</tableCitation>
). It is also reminiscent of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Maguire &amp; J. R. Laundon" baseAuthorityName="Klotzsch ex Diels" baseAuthorityYear="1906" box="[1238,1375,951,976]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Droseraceae" genus="Drosera" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="roraimae">
<emphasis box="[1238,1375,951,976]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">D. roraimae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, being distinct from it by the smaller size, decumbent leaves (
<emphasis box="[736,759,987,1012]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">vs</emphasis>
. semi-erect), scape base erect (Fig. 12e; 
<emphasis box="[1207,1230,987,1012]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">vs</emphasis>
. curved), and ovoid seeds with foveolate testa (
<emphasis box="[439,462,1023,1048]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">vs</emphasis>
. ellipsoid seeds with reticulate testa).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="35.[136,1452,482,1517]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">
In contrast to the concept of 
<bibRefCitation author="Correa A. &amp; Silva, T. R. S." box="[505,756,1058,1085]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" refId="ref53788" refString="Correa A., M. D. &amp; Silva, T. R. S. (2005) Drosera (Droseraceae). Flora Neotropica Monograph 96. The New York Botanical Garden Press, New York, 65 pp." type="book" year="2005">
Correa &amp; 
<taxonomicName authority="Gonella &amp; Sano &amp; Rivadavia &amp; Fleischmann, 2022" authorityName="Gonella &amp; Sano &amp; Rivadavia &amp; Fleischmann" authorityYear="2022" box="[615,673,1058,1084]" class="Aves" family="Leiothrichidae" genus="Silva" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Passeriformes" pageId="35" pageNumber="74" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus" status="N.G.">Silva</taxonomicName>
(2005)
</bibRefCitation>
, which included 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Maguire &amp; Wurdack" authorityYear="1957" baseAuthorityName="Steyermark" baseAuthorityYear="1952" box="[944,1106,1058,1084]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Droseraceae" genus="Drosera" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="esmeraldae">
<emphasis box="[944,1106,1058,1084]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">D. esmeraldae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
under synonymy of 
<taxonomicName box="[1335,1444,1058,1084]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Droseraceae" genus="Drosera" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="biflora">
<emphasis box="[1335,1444,1058,1084]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">D. biflora</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, we here consider these taxa distinct based on leaf, scape, sepal and seed morphology (
<tableCitation box="[1098,1185,1094,1120]" captionStart="TABLE 3" captionStartId="21.[136,229,1487,1513]" captionTargetId="graphics-577@21.[136,1449,1593,1971]" captionTargetPageId="21" captionText="TABLE 3. Diagnostic characters distinguishing between Drosera amazonica, D. biflora, D. capillaris (only specimens" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">Table 3</tableCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="35.[136,1452,482,1517]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">
Hybridization and introgression between 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Maguire &amp; Wurdack" authorityYear="1957" baseAuthorityName="Steyermark" baseAuthorityYear="1952" box="[655,818,1130,1156]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Droseraceae" genus="Drosera" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="esmeraldae">
<emphasis box="[655,818,1130,1156]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">D. esmeraldae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Maguire &amp; J. R. Laundon" baseAuthorityName="Klotzsch ex Diels" baseAuthorityYear="1906" box="[874,1012,1131,1156]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Droseraceae" genus="Drosera" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="roraimae">
<emphasis box="[874,1012,1131,1156]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">D. roraimae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are suspected to occur in places where both are syntopic, e.g. the Serra do Aracá, resulting in plants with intermediate features (such as the specimen 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">Rivadavia et al. 784</emphasis>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
